* {{ill|Bunji|ja|文治|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} 5th year（{{ill|Julian calendar|ja|ユリウス暦|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}  {{ill|1189|ja|1189|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}  {{ill|November 2|ja|11月2日|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} ） – {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}  appointed {{ill|Kōzaisei Kiyoshige|ja|葛西清重|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}  as the chief administrator (奥州総奉行), thereby consolidating control over Ōshu.
* {{ill|Tenwa (Japan)|ja|天和|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} 3rd year（{{ill|Gregorian calendar|ja|グレゴリオ暦|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}  {{ill|1683|ja|1683|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}  {{ill|November 10|ja|11月10日|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} ） – In Kyoto, the wife of the great Buddhist priest (大経師) – known as {{ill|O-san and Tedai Shigehei|ja|おさんと手代茂兵衛|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}  – was executed for adultery. This incident provided material for works such as {{ill|Nishikaze’s|ja|西鶴|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}  "Kōshoku Gonin Onna" and {{ill|Chikamatsu’s|ja|近松|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}  "Daikyōshi Mukireki".
* {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} 1st year（{{ill|Gregorian calendar|ja|グレゴリオ暦|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}  {{ill|1868|ja|1868|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}  {{ill|November 6|ja|11月6日|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} ） – The lord of the Aizu domain, {{ill|Matsudaira Katamori|ja|松平容保|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} , opened his castle ({{Tsurugajo}} ) by "opening the castle" ceremony; Aizu later surrendered to the imperial forces.

